  "coreFormingSummary": "Gather soil and compress it into a tight sphere.",
  "coreFormingStep1": "Find soil with a mix of clay and fine sand — avoid pure clay or sandy soil.",
  "coreFormingStep2": "Add water gradually until the soil holds together when squeezed.",
  "coreFormingStep3": "Form a rough ball about the size of a tennis ball.",
  "coreFormingStep4": "Squeeze and compact firmly, rotating constantly to keep it round.",
  "coreFormingStep5": "Continue compressing for 15–20 minutes until the core feels solid.",
  "coreFormingTip": "The core should feel dense and heavy for its size. If it crumbles, add a tiny bit more water.",
  "coreFormingMistake": "Too much water makes the core sticky and hard to shape. Start drier than you think.",
  "coreFormingVoice": "Time to form your core. Find soil with a good mix of clay and fine sand. Add water gradually and squeeze it into a tight ball, about tennis ball sized. Keep rotating and compressing for fifteen to twenty minutes until it feels solid and dense.",

  "dryingSummary": "Let moisture migrate to the surface while maintaining shape.",
  "dryingStep1": "Place the sphere on a soft surface or hold it gently.",
  "dryingStep2": "Wait 20–30 minutes for moisture to migrate to the surface.",
  "dryingStep3": "When the surface feels damp, gently brush off any loose material.",
  "dryingStep4": "Repeat the drying cycle — this stage may take several hours.",
  "dryingStep5": "The sphere is ready for dusting when the surface no longer feels wet.",
  "dryingTip": "Patience is everything here. Rushing to the next stage will cause cracks.",
  "dryingMistake": "Letting it dry too fast in direct sun causes surface cracks. Dry slowly in shade.",
  "dryingVoice": "Now we dry. Place your sphere down gently and wait twenty to thirty minutes for moisture to reach the surface. When it feels damp, brush off loose material. Repeat this cycle. The sphere is ready for dusting when the surface no longer feels wet. This takes patience — usually several hours.",

  "dustingCappingSummary": "Apply layers of fine dry soil to build a smooth outer shell.",
  "dustingCappingStep1": "Sift soil through a fine mesh to get ultra-fine dry powder.",
  "dustingCappingStep2": "Sprinkle a thin layer of powder over the sphere.",
  "dustingCappingStep3": "Gently rub the powder into the surface using your palm or thumb.",
  "dustingCappingStep4": "Let it rest for 10–15 minutes between coats.",
  "dustingCappingStep5": "Apply 5–10 coats until the surface is uniformly smooth.",
  "dustingCappingTip": "The finer the dust, the better the final shine. Use the finest particles you can find.",
  "dustingCappingMistake": "Applying dust too thick causes flaking. Thin, even layers are the key.",
  "dustingCappingVoice": "Time to dust and cap. Sift your soil to get the finest powder possible. Sprinkle a thin layer over the sphere and gently rub it in with your palm. Rest ten to fifteen minutes between coats. Apply five to ten coats until the surface is uniformly smooth.",

  "polishingSummary": "Burnish the surface to bring out a natural shine.",
  "polishingStep1": "Make sure the surface is completely dry to the touch.",
  "polishingStep2": "Using a smooth surface (plastic bag, glass jar, or soft cloth), gently rub the sphere.",
  "polishingStep3": "Apply light, consistent pressure in circular motions.",
  "polishingStep4": "Work the entire surface, rotating frequently for even shine.",
  "polishingStep5": "Continue for 30–60 minutes. The shine develops gradually.",
  "polishingTip": "Less pressure is more. Let the tool glide — forcing it can gouge the surface.",
  "polishingMistake": "Polishing before fully dry embeds moisture and causes dull spots.",
  "polishingVoice": "Time to polish. Make sure the surface is completely dry. Using a smooth surface like a plastic bag or glass jar, gently rub the sphere in circular motions. Keep the pressure light and consistent. Work the entire surface for thirty to sixty minutes. The shine will develop gradually.",

